[1] Cholera - Uganda (Kabarole) Asia
Date: Mon 21 Jun 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com and The Monitor (Kampala) [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200406210563.html>

Cholera hits Kabarole
---------------------
A cholera epidemic has hit Kabarole district, leaving 4 people dead in
Mitandi, Buhesi sub-county. The [doctor] in charge at Bunyangabu health
center, Dr Akasiima, said that the affected had gone to Hima, Kasese for
the burial of their relatives. This is where they contracted the disease,
which has spread to different parts of Kasese and Kabarole districts.
They are all residents of Mitandi, Buhesi sub-county. Akasiima said the
situation was under control, and health workers were working hard to get
information to the residents about how to live in a clean environment by
washing their hands before and after eating food.
The director of health services, Dr Kabagambe Rugamba, earlier told
reporters that a van from the Ministry of Health had been in Kabarole
educating people about their hygiene. The LC 3 chairperson of Buhesi
sub-county, Mr Moses Ikagobya, reminded residents to maintain good sanitary
conditions in order to survive the epidemic.
[byline: Joseph Kasimba]
******
[2] Cholera, amoebic dysentery - Philippines (Pangasinan)
Date: Sun 20 Jun 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Manila Bulletin Online [edited]
<http://www.mb.com.ph/PROV2004062012279.html>

Gastroenteritis in Pangasinan still unchecked; action plan set
----------------------------------------------
Health and provincial officials held an emergency meeting on Thu 17 Jun
2004 to prepare an immediate action plan in response to the growing number
of patients suffering from gastroenteritis -- specifically cholera and
amoebic dysentery -- in several towns of Pangasinan.
The meeting was called by provincial administrator Virgilio Solis at a time
when these waterborne diseases have already affected some 230 people in
Malasiqui, 141 people in San Carlos City, 22 people in Basista, and a still
undetermined number in Mangaldan and San Fabian. Solis mobilized all
concerned government agencies in Pangasinan, national and local, to help
control the spread of the disease in whatever way they can in order to ease
the suffering of the patients.
Up until noon of Thu 17 Jun 2004, the disease appeared not to be unchecked
in San Carlos City, as 24 more patients were brought in for confinement at
the Pangasinan Provincial Hospital (PPH). Luckily, the patients were
recovering, after 2 days of treatment.
Dr Policarpio Manuel, chief of the clinic of the PPH, said that, because of
the large numbers of patients coming in, even the aisles of both floors of
the hospital were being used as temporary wards for patients. For lack of
beds, patients had to be laid on benches pulled out from the chapel.
Manuel ruled out the possibility that the disease is now of epidemic
proportions, because it has not yet affected the whole of Pangasinan,
adding that it remains at an endemic stage. Alarmed by the discovery that 6
of the patients from Malasiqui were positive for _Vibrio cholerae_ El Tor,
provincial officials rallied all public hospitals, and medical personnel,
to admit all patients and to control the spread of the diseases.
******
[3] Cholera - Pakistan (Spin Boldak Afghan Refugee Camp)
Date: Fri 25 Jun 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: PakTribune.com [edited]
<http://paktribune.com/news/index.php?id=68759>

4 more kids die of cholera outbreak in SBARC
--------------------------------------------
The death toll in the cholera outbreak in Spin Boldak Afghan refugee camp
(SBARC) reached 25 on Fri 25 Jun 2004. 4 more children have died. The
epidemic disease has, so far, affected older people and children, but there
is fear of a larger outbreak due to severe weather conditions, water
shortage, and lack of proper medicine.
Afghan refugees, talking to reporters who visited the camp, said that the
scorching heat, the shortage of water, and the scarcity of medicines are
augmenting the death toll. The government of Pakistan must address the
situation by providing clean drinking water and proper medicines in the
refugee camps to prevent further loss of life, they declared.
