[4] Cholera - Belgium ex India
Date: Tue 22 Jun 2004
From: Germaine Hanquet <germaine.hanquet@iph.fgov.be>
Source: Infectious diseases in the spotlights : 2004 [edited]
<http://www.iph.fgov.be/epidemio/epien/plaben/idnews/index_fr.htm>

An imported case of cholera in Brussels
---------------------------------------
A confirmed case of cholera was reported to the Brussels health inspection
on 6 Jun 2004. The patient, a 43 year old woman, left India on 2 Jun 2004
for a tour of Europe. She was struck with profuse diarrhea on 3 Jun 2004,
during her trip between London and Brussels, and was admitted, upon her
arrival at a Brussels hospital, for hypovolemic shock. She has been treated
in an intensive care unit under isolation and stabilized with IV
rehydration and doxycycline. Her prognosis is favorable.
_Vibrio cholerae_ was isolated from her urine, on 6 Jun 2004, and in stool
culture the following day. Further testing has been performed at the _V.
cholerae_ Reference Laboratory at the Liege University Hospital, which
identified the organism as a _V. cholerae_ O1 serotype Inaba.
Control measures have been carried out in collaboration with the hospital
staff, the Brussels health inspection, the Scientific Institute of Public
Health (IPH), and the Federal Warning Unit. Close contacts (2 family
members) have been monitored and given prophylaxis. Hospital staff have
been informed, and hygiene control measures have been applied at the
hospital. The ambulance company has been warned to apply adequate
disinfection, as have the airline and the London-Brussels train companies.
Since other people traveling in the same group have continued their trip
through Europe, European health authorities were informed through the Early
Alert and Warning System on 7 Jun 2004.
Cholera is transmitted by drinking water, or eating food, contaminated by
large numbers of _V. cholerae_. The disease is unlikely to spread from one
person to another, and casual contact with an infected person is not a risk
factor for becoming ill. In Europe, the risk of disease is extremely low,
even in travelers. However, all travelers to areas where cholera has
occurred should observe the usual hygiene recommendations: drink safe
water, eat cooked food, avoid raw vegetables, etc.
--
Germaine Hanquet, MD, MPH
Scientific Institute of Public Health - Louis Pasteur
Brussels, Belgium
<G.hanquet@iph.fgov.be>
